# Rust Development Standards

Use this rule for all Rust service work.

## Readability and structure
- Prefer explicit, boring Rust over clever type gymnastics when maintainability is the priority.
- Keep ownership, borrowing, and mutation easy to follow.
- Split files or helper types when a module starts mixing protocol parsing, orchestration, I/O, and state transitions.
- Prefer domain-specific types over loosely structured tuples or ad hoc maps in non-trivial code.

## Error handling
- Prefer returning `Result` and propagating errors with context.
- Use `thiserror` or domain error enums when callers need structured handling.
- Avoid `unwrap` and `expect` in production paths unless an invariant is truly process-fatal and the comment explains why.
- Treat retries, fallback behavior, and ignored failures as design decisions that deserve comments.

## Async and lifecycle
- Make task ownership, cancellation, and shutdown behavior explicit.
- Use shared state sparingly and document invariants around locks or caches.
- Prefer message passing or well-scoped state holders over broad shared mutability.
- If blocking work is required inside async flows, isolate it clearly.

## Comments
- Add comments for protocol details, lifecycle assumptions, cache coherence, system integration caveats, and amendment hazards.
- Comments may be longer than usual when preserving operational trade-offs or maintenance constraints.
- Do not comment syntax that the type system already makes clear.

## Testing and quality
- Run `cargo fmt --all`.
- Run `cargo check --all-targets --all-features`.
- Run `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings`.
- Run `cargo test --all-targets --all-features`.
- Prefer focused unit tests for parsing, state logic, and error handling.
- Add integration-style coverage when behavior crosses async boundaries, filesystem boundaries, or service contracts.

## Lint posture
- Keep Clippy clean in touched code.
- Prefer explicit helper functions and typed constants when Clippy is surfacing readability issues.
- Do not silence Clippy without a narrow explanation.
